The rate of occurrence for when the participant/subject consumes six or more drinks containing alcohol on one occasion. It is noted that the meaning of &quot;drinks consumed&quot; differs from one nation and culture to another, so the most common alcoholic beverages likely to be consumed will be defined as well as quantity of each that constitutes a drink (approximately 10 grams of pure ethanol). For example, one bottle of beer (330 ml at 5% ethanol), a glass of wine (140 ml at 12% ethanol), and a shot of spirits (40 ml at 40% ethanol) represent a standard drink of about 13 g of ethanol.
Indicator of whether the participant/subject has been hospitalized for an alcohol-related problem (i.e., esophageal varices, delirium tremens (DTs), cirrhosis and others)
